$$X$$ [[Topological space]], $$x_0 \in X$$

[[Definition|https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Lcu93_AfTQw&list=PLLq_gUfXAnkl8bjQh-hGQ9u24xZP9x0dx&index=16#t=32m15s]] of the ''fundamental group'' with ''base point'' at $$x_0$$:

:$$\pi_1(X,x_0) = \{[f] | f: I \to X \text{ a path} | f(0) = f(1) = x_0\}$$ ([[Homotopy class]]es of [[Closed path]]s starting/ending at $$x_0$$).

Here we are using [[Path homotopy]] as we are using paths.

See also [[this video|https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uBDYSPMyaRQ&list=PLLq_gUfXAnkkdRttylq7Svmob1gxDgcDZ]], and [[these notes|https://courses.maths.ox.ac.uk/node/view_material/33583#page=23]]

!!!__Product__

The product for making it into a [[Group]] is the [[Product of paths]] lifted to their homotopy classes (as explained in [[Path homotopy]]). It is always defined for the above set because they all start and end in the same point.

$$[f]*[g] = [f*g]$$

(where $$*$$ for paths is the [[Product of paths]])

The unit element is the constant path $$c_{x_0}$$.

$$[f]^{-1} = [f^{-1}]$$

__Example__
[[For R^n|https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Lcu93_AfTQw&list=PLLq_gUfXAnkl8bjQh-hGQ9u24xZP9x0dx&index=16#t=37m18s]], it is the [[Trivial group]] using [[Straight line homotopy]]

[[pi_1 of circle|https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Lcu93_AfTQw&list=PLLq_gUfXAnkl8bjQh-hGQ9u24xZP9x0dx&index=16#t=1h6m30s]] $$\cong \mathbb{Z}$$

!!!__Fundamental group from [[Triangulation]]__

The group of equivalence classes of edge loops under 'elementary deformations' for a [[Triangulation]] of space X is a finite combinatorial object, easier to compute, and it is [[isomorphic|Group isomorphism]] to the fundamental group of the space X. 

See [[here|https://courses.maths.ox.ac.uk/node/view_material/33583#page=30]]

