__Functor__

[[Def|https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Lcu93_AfTQw&list=PLLq_gUfXAnkl8bjQh-hGQ9u24xZP9x0dx&index=16#t=1h8m15s]]:

Let $$h: X \to Y$$ be a [[Continuous function]] with $$h(x_0) = y_0$$. Define

$$h_*: \pi(X,x_0) \to \pi_1(Y,y_0)$$

$$h_* ([f]) = [h \circ f]$$

This is a [[Group homomorphism]] induced by $$h$$.

[[Functorial properties of the map|https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Lcu93_AfTQw&list=PLLq_gUfXAnkl8bjQh-hGQ9u24xZP9x0dx&index=16#t=1h14m14s]]

$$X \to_f Y \to_g Z$$

$$f(x_0) = y_0$$, $$g(y_0) = z_0$$

=> $$(g \circ f)_* = g_* \circ f_*$$

identity map $$(id_X)_* = id_{\pi_1(X,x_0)}$$ 

See also [[this vid|https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uBDYSPMyaRQ&list=PLLq_gUfXAnkkdRttylq7Svmob1gxDgcDZ#t=1h5m30s]].

[[Theorem|https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Lcu93_AfTQw&list=PLLq_gUfXAnkl8bjQh-hGQ9u24xZP9x0dx&index=16#t=1h22m]]. If $$f: X \to Y$$ is a [[Homeomorphism]], $$f(x_0) = y_0$$, then $$f_*: \pi_1(X,x_0) \to \pi_1 (Y,y_0)$$ is n [[Isomorphism]].

[[Remark|https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Lcu93_AfTQw&list=PLLq_gUfXAnkl8bjQh-hGQ9u24xZP9x0dx&index=16#t=1h26m55s]]. I $$X$$ and $$Y$$ are path-connected and $$\pi_1(X,x_0)$$ is not isomorphic to $$\pi_1(Y,y_0)$$ then $$X$$ and $$Y$$ are not homeomorphic.

[[Fundamental group|https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Lcu93_AfTQw&list=PLLq_gUfXAnkl8bjQh-hGQ9u24xZP9x0dx&index=16#t=1h30m25s]] $$(\pi(X,x_0),h_*)$$ is a [[Functor]] from the [[Category]] of topological spaces with base points and continuous base-point-preserving maps to the category of groups and group homomorphisms.

